# The committed sample dataset (docs/samples/, DATA-SPEC §9.5) is compared
# byte-for-byte against a fresh build by the I16 drift guard, so Git must hand
# the working tree exactly the bytes the blob holds — no line-ending rewriting
# in either direction.
#
# This is safe to state for the whole tree because the builder is now
# deterministic about line endings on its own: everything text goes through
# `sidecar.textio`, which writes LF on every platform, and the two CSV families
# come from `csv.writer`, whose CRLF row terminator is part of RFC 4180 rather
# than a property of the host. Before that, the .json and .md samples emitted
# the platform's own ending, and the guard passed on Windows only because
# core.autocrlf=true happened to smudge the checkout back into agreement with
# the build -- so `autocrlf=false` failed, and pinning them here would have
# failed too. Neither is true now: the bytes are the same everywhere.
docs/samples/** -text
